  "doc_id": "20242",
  "text": "Crown architecture is a compound trait resulting from the position, size, periodicity, angle and density of the branches. Crown characteristics affect plantation density, interception of photosynthetic light and quality of the derived wood. Depending on the plantation purpose, the direction and extent to which these characteristics need to be changed can vary. Branches originate in axillary meristems (AMs) and thus establishment and outgrowth of AMs has a profound effect on branch characteristics and crown architecture. AM initiation is exclusively characterized in herbaceous plants and there is no information about the effect of these genes in trees. We therefore will not cover here these developments. Excellent reviews on AM initiation discuss in detail these genes and mechanisms [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] .",
